:INFO
What a Starter Actually Is
A sourdough starter is a live culture of wild yeast and lactic acid bacteria. \
You feed it flour and water, and it ferments. That gas is what leavens your bread \
without any commercial yeast at all.

:COUNTER.half
50 Grams
Flour per feeding
|
50 Grams
Water per feeding

:PATH
Day 1: Mix and Wait
Combine 50g whole wheat flour and 50g room-temperature water in a clean jar.
|
:INFO
Day 1: Mix and Wait
Combine 50g whole wheat flour and 50g room-temperature water in a clean jar. Stir well, \
cover loosely, and leave at room temperature (around 21 to 24 C).

:PATH
Days 2 to 4: Discard and Feed
Each day, discard all but 50g of starter, then add 50g flour and 50g water.
|
:INFO
Days 2 to 4: Discard and Feed
Each day, discard all but 50g of starter, then add 50g flour and 50g water. Stir \
vigorously to incorporate air. You may see some bubbles by day 3.

:PATH
Days 5 to 7: Watch for Activity
Your starter is ready when it reliably doubles in size within 4 to 8 hours of
|
:INFO
Days 5 to 7: Watch for Activity
Your starter is ready when it reliably doubles in size within 4 to 8 hours of feeding, \
smells pleasantly sour or fruity, and has a domed top before it collapses.

:PATH
The Float Test
Drop a small spoonful into a glass of water.
|
:INFO
The Float Test
Drop a small spoonful into a glass of water. If it floats, it has enough gas and is \
ready to bake with. A starter that sinks needs more time or more feedings.

:NOTE
Long-Term Storage
Once active, keep your starter in the fridge and feed it once a week. \
Pull it out the night before baking, feed it, and let it peak at room temperature \
before using. Whole wheat or rye flour accelerates activity in sluggish starters.

:QUOTE
The starter does not care about your schedule. Build the habit of feeding it \
and it will reward you every single bake.
